{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17616720","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17616720"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:06:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:06:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16417"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16417","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16417"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9108"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75966"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9108","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9108"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16417"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61467"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"8663"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21631"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21633"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75966","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75966"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe brain\u0027s ability to adapt and change in response to experiences and environmental stimuli varies throughout life. This property, known as neuroplasticity, is particularly important during development.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the pattern of neuroplasticity across the human lifespan?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Peaks in early years then completely ceases in adulthood","Gradually increases from birth to reach maximum in adulthood","Remains constant from birth through to old age","Peaks in early years then gradually declines but persists","Fluctuates randomly throughout development and adulthood"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe brain demonstrates \u003Cstrong\u003Epeaks in early years then gradually declines but persists\u003C/strong\u003E throughout life. This pattern allows for rapid learning and adaptation during critical developmental periods while maintaining some capacity for change in adulthood.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeaks in early years then completely ceases in adulthood\u003C/strong\u003E - Adults retain the ability to learn and form new neural connections, though at a reduced rate\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGradually increases from birth to reach maximum in adulthood\u003C/strong\u003E - Early childhood represents a period of maximum plasticity which then decreases\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERemains constant from birth through to old age\u003C/strong\u003E - Plasticity shows clear age-related changes rather than remaining stable\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFluctuates randomly throughout development and adulthood\u003C/strong\u003E - Changes in plasticity follow a predictable pattern rather than random fluctuations\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis pattern of plasticity explains why early intervention is crucial for developmental conditions, while still allowing for rehabilitation and learning in adults after injury or stroke.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Brain plasticity is highest during early development and gradually decreases with age but never completely disappears.","Neuroplasticity allows the brain to form new neural connections and reorganise existing ones throughout life.","Critical periods in early development show enhanced plasticity for specific functions like vision and language."],"references":["Price RB, Duman R. Neuroplasticity in cognitive and psychological mechanisms of depression: an integrative model. Mol Psychiatry. 2020 Mar;25(3):530-543. doi: 10.1038/s41380-019-0615-x. Epub 2019 Dec 4. PMID: 31801966; PMCID: PMC7047599.","Fuchs E, Fl\u00fcgge G. Adult neuroplasticity: more than 40 years of research. Neural Plast. 2014;2014:541870. doi: 10.1155/2014/541870. Epub 2014 May 4. PMID: 24883212; PMCID: PMC4026979.","Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022).\u00a0The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61467"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16417"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61467","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61467"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-01T18:39:37+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-01T18:40:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9108"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75966"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags